  <div class="col-lg-8 offset-lg-2 col-md-8 mb-4 mb-md-0" style="position: relative; z-index: 1;">
    <div class="case-study-info">
      <p>The column selector was a massive hit with stakeholders/product owners. Paired with the simple pinning functionality (the pin icon in the top right locks your table configuration) it gives teams the ability to display information that might not be primary to every user, but could be configured to be optimally useful and actionable based on that users personal workflow.</p>
      <p>Keeping pinning simple leaves lots of room in the future for a "custom filter" builder concept. A paid feature on our long-term roadmap.</p>
      <p>Column can now be dragged to resize. While this meant we'd have to have a truncation strategy for every cell, the benefit to the user was high. Columns also announce their sortability now, giving users this knowledge without a time-consuming click.</p>
      <p><a href="https://www.figma.com/file/MS55iohbSNcfmlIqQv3KRZ/Admin-Incidents-%26-Hazards-Data-Tables?type=design&node-id=0%3A1&mode=design&t=wHGu9vdN4tImCSCp-1" target="_blank">Check out a table project exmple in Figma here</a></p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="col-lg-12 my-4 my-lg-5" style="position: relative; z-index: 1;">
    <img src="/images/projects/data-tables/04.png" class="img-fluid super-shadow rounded-3" alt="">
    <figcaption style="text-align: center;">Fractional distribution with minimum widths (and horizontal scroll below that) eliminates chainsawing</figcaption>
  </div>
  <div class="col-lg-8 offset-lg-2 col-md-8 mb-4 mb-md-0" style="position: relative; z-index: 1;">
    <div class="case-study-info">
      <p>While it's certainly nothing new to the web, fraction distribution has made a massive increase to the readability of a table row. All table cells were designed with a line-return and truncation strategy to accommodate this.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

